WEBVTT

00:05.999 --> 00:10.404
**

00:10.404 --> 00:12.806
The year was 1963.

00:12.806 --> 00:15.576
The first James Bond
film Dr. No

00:15.576 --> 00:17.778
was a hit in the theaters...

00:17.778 --> 00:20.280
* Here's a little song you
can all join in with *

00:20.280 --> 00:22.583
* It's very simple
and I hope it's new, yeah *

00:22.583 --> 00:27.788
Coca-Cola introduced a new
calorie-free soda called Tab

00:27.788 --> 00:31.024
and a little-known band from
Liverpool named the Beatles

00:31.024 --> 00:34.862
had shot up to the top
of the charts in the UK.

00:34.862 --> 00:39.633
**

00:39.633 --> 00:42.436
But on November 22nd
of that year,

00:42.436 --> 00:46.974
the assassination of John F.
Kennedy changed everything.

00:46.974 --> 00:50.811
**

00:50.811 --> 00:53.447
While the country
was still in shock,

00:53.447 --> 00:56.049
I was in the midst
of a trial,

00:56.049 --> 00:58.852
facing jail time
on obscenity charges

00:58.852 --> 01:01.722
for publishing nude pictures
of actress Jayne Mansfield

01:01.722 --> 01:06.293
in the pages
of Playboy magazine.

01:06.293 --> 01:09.363
**

01:13.467 --> 01:16.804
After weeks of arguments,

01:16.804 --> 01:21.742
it was finally time
to hear the verdict.

01:21.742 --> 01:24.111
Bailiff...

01:32.285 --> 01:35.656
I know what pornography is
and I know what obscenity is,

01:35.656 --> 01:37.791
and it certainly isn't
Playboy and never has been.

01:37.791 --> 01:43.130
But again, we were questioning
the traditional values,

01:43.130 --> 01:45.365
and that context, I think,

01:45.365 --> 01:47.034
is what got us
into the most trouble.

01:53.240 --> 01:56.109
Defendant, please rise.

02:01.214 --> 02:02.683
On the counts of publishing

02:02.683 --> 02:05.553
and distributing
an obscene publication,

02:05.553 --> 02:10.724
the jury has been unable
to reach a verdict.

02:10.724 --> 02:13.260
Mr. Hefner,
you are free to go.

02:13.260 --> 02:16.797
**

02:16.797 --> 02:18.065
* All right *

02:18.065 --> 02:20.701
**

02:20.701 --> 02:23.937
* I been a-hopin'
and a-prayin' *

02:23.937 --> 02:25.906
* For such a long time *

02:25.906 --> 02:28.609
The jury was deadlocked
7 to 5

02:28.609 --> 02:30.010
in favor of acquittal...

02:30.010 --> 02:31.779
**

02:31.779 --> 02:34.347
...and all charges
against me were dropped.

02:34.347 --> 02:36.149
* Ain't it a good thing? *

02:36.149 --> 02:37.651
**

02:37.651 --> 02:39.487
* Ain't it a good thing? *

02:39.487 --> 02:40.621
**

02:40.621 --> 02:42.355
I felt relieved

02:42.355 --> 02:46.093
and like I'd won a major
victory for free speech.

02:46.093 --> 02:47.194
**

02:47.194 --> 02:50.030
* Oh, ain't it
a good thing? *

02:50.030 --> 02:51.231
**

02:51.231 --> 02:53.033
My fight was finally over,

02:53.033 --> 02:55.569
but world events
were about to reshape

02:55.569 --> 02:58.238
the country and Playboy.

02:58.238 --> 03:01.709
**

03:01.709 --> 03:05.345
* Every little movement *

03:05.345 --> 03:09.850
* Every little thing
you do *

03:09.850 --> 03:12.285
* Is it sleight of hand *

03:12.285 --> 03:17.457
* That commands my heart
to love you? *

03:17.457 --> 03:21.261
* Every little movement *

03:21.261 --> 03:25.232
* Every
little movement **

03:25.232 --> 03:27.835
**

03:39.412 --> 03:42.215
With the obscenity case
behind us,

03:42.215 --> 03:44.284
Playboy spent
the next two years

03:44.284 --> 03:47.120
getting back to business,
publishing centerfolds

03:47.120 --> 03:50.824
next to articles
promoting social justice.

03:50.824 --> 03:55.095
But by 1965,
there was one issue

03:55.095 --> 03:58.599
that overshadowed
all the others.

04:00.734 --> 04:02.636
This is the hot spot
in the Cold War

04:02.636 --> 04:04.572
and this year saw it
getting hotter.

04:04.572 --> 04:07.074
* The Eastern world *

04:07.074 --> 04:08.642
* It is exploding *

04:08.642 --> 04:10.110
* Violence flaring *

04:10.110 --> 04:11.411
America had been locked

04:11.411 --> 04:13.346
in conflict in Vietnam

04:13.346 --> 04:15.182
since the mid '50s,

04:15.182 --> 04:17.017
but every year,
our involvement

04:17.017 --> 04:19.086
in the war kept increasing.

04:19.086 --> 04:24.391
In 1963, there were
16,000 troops in Vietnam.

04:24.391 --> 04:28.495
By '65, there were 125,000.

04:28.495 --> 04:30.898
* Oh you don't believe *

04:30.898 --> 04:34.334
* We're on the eve
of destruction *

04:34.334 --> 04:37.370
Vietnam starts off
with, uh, oh,

04:37.370 --> 04:38.672
we're just gonna
be contained,

04:38.672 --> 04:40.608
and military advisors here

04:40.608 --> 04:42.009
that'll support
the government

04:42.009 --> 04:43.811
at this resistance
to tyranny,

04:43.811 --> 04:46.013
and then it escalated
and escalated,

04:46.013 --> 04:48.281
and more and more,
uh, kids are being sent

04:48.281 --> 04:51.484
over to Vietnam, and more
and more kids are dying.

04:51.484 --> 04:52.586
* Can't you feel
the fears *

04:52.586 --> 04:54.454
* I'm feeling today? *

04:54.454 --> 04:56.624
With more casualties
every day,

04:56.624 --> 04:59.893
demonstrators took
to the streets

04:59.893 --> 05:02.329
and young men began
burning their draft cards.

05:02.329 --> 05:04.564
* Take a look
around you, boy *

05:04.564 --> 05:07.601
* It's bound to scare you,
boy, and you tell me *

05:07.601 --> 05:09.569
Never before
had an American war

05:09.569 --> 05:11.905
been protested so openly,

05:11.905 --> 05:14.642
and I knew the voices
of these young radicals

05:14.642 --> 05:16.576
belonged in Playboy.

05:16.576 --> 05:21.615
* We're on the eve
of destruction **

05:26.153 --> 05:29.356
So I hired a new
assistant editor...

05:29.356 --> 05:34.594
**

05:34.594 --> 05:37.530
* We'll call you when
you're six years old *

05:37.530 --> 05:39.232
...a popular
young journalist

05:39.232 --> 05:41.401
who had written
politically-charged pieces

05:41.401 --> 05:44.638
for The Village Voice
named Arthur Kretchmer.

05:44.638 --> 05:47.775
* To train your brain
for 18 years *

05:47.775 --> 05:51.344
I was hired with a bunch
of other hip, connected,

05:51.344 --> 05:53.313
intelligent young people.

05:53.313 --> 05:55.515
Some of us were smoking dope.

05:55.515 --> 06:00.788
Some of us were emphatically
against the Vietnam War.

06:00.788 --> 06:01.822
I think all of our editors

06:01.822 --> 06:03.691
were a little bit
to the left,

06:03.691 --> 06:06.760
but Arthur represented
his generation

06:06.760 --> 06:09.529
and he was well connected
with that world.

06:09.529 --> 06:15.969
**

06:15.969 --> 06:18.371
Next we have a piece

06:18.371 --> 06:20.107
for our attire section.

06:20.107 --> 06:22.275
No man, no matter
how fashion-conscious,

06:22.275 --> 06:25.045
enjoys having to spend
days or even weeks

06:25.045 --> 06:27.480
breaking in
a new pair of shoes.

06:27.480 --> 06:31.118
Jesus Christ.

06:31.118 --> 06:33.821
I'm sorry, did you have
something to contribute?

06:33.821 --> 06:36.389
Yeah. Who cares?

06:36.389 --> 06:38.391
Seriously, who gives a shit?

06:38.391 --> 06:40.227
There's a war
going on out there,

06:40.227 --> 06:41.561
and we're sitting
around here bickering

06:41.561 --> 06:42.830
about how many days
it takes

06:42.830 --> 06:45.065
to break in a pair
of goddamn shoes.

06:45.065 --> 06:48.101
Last month,
100,000 Americans

06:48.101 --> 06:50.237
demonstrated in cities
across the country.

06:50.237 --> 06:53.006
Last week, a man stood
in front of the Pentagon,

06:53.006 --> 06:56.409
doused himself in kerosene,
and set himself on fire.

06:56.409 --> 06:58.278
And what the hell
are we doing about it?

06:58.278 --> 07:01.381
What the hell is
Playboy saying about it?

07:01.381 --> 07:03.851
Nothing.

07:05.218 --> 07:06.887
In case you haven't
noticed,

07:06.887 --> 07:09.322
you're no longer working
at The Village Voice.

07:09.322 --> 07:11.992
Let them cover those
types of stories.

07:11.992 --> 07:14.427
No, I think we should have
something to say about it.

07:14.427 --> 07:18.365
If it matters to us,
it matters to our readers.

07:18.365 --> 07:23.370
Bring in an article.
If it's good, I'll run it.

07:23.370 --> 07:24.772
Shall I continue?

07:24.772 --> 07:26.306
Mm-hmm.

07:28.008 --> 07:31.945
For our humor section,

07:31.945 --> 07:34.848
a fresh slate
of party jokes.

07:37.350 --> 07:42.355
Spectorsky and I
developed conflict,

07:42.355 --> 07:45.258
and Spectorsky hated
the word "political"

07:45.258 --> 07:46.626
and hated politics.

07:46.626 --> 07:48.896
I really did represent
something

07:48.896 --> 07:50.663
that he wasn't ready for.

07:50.663 --> 07:54.434
**

07:54.434 --> 07:56.937
* There is a man *

07:56.937 --> 07:59.039
* A tall man *

07:59.039 --> 08:00.407
* Follows no... *

08:00.407 --> 08:02.175
Soon Kretchmer pushed us

08:02.175 --> 08:04.211
to take a stance
on the Vietnam War.

08:04.211 --> 08:05.879
* Out in a storm *

08:05.879 --> 08:07.347
* Can he stay warm *

08:07.347 --> 08:10.217
But he didn't stop there.

08:10.217 --> 08:13.153
Britain recently abolished
the death penalty.

08:13.153 --> 08:14.988
If we're supposed to be the
freest country in the world,

08:14.988 --> 08:16.756
why are we one of
the few western nations

08:16.756 --> 08:19.559
that hasn't banned
capital punishment?

08:19.559 --> 08:20.961
* Can't he move on? *

08:20.961 --> 08:22.963
* Tell him it's all right *

08:22.963 --> 08:26.066
We called for the abolition
of the death penalty,

08:26.066 --> 08:28.936
arguing not only
that it was barbaric

08:28.936 --> 08:31.138
but that it was
disproportionately used

08:31.138 --> 08:32.873
against poor people.

08:32.873 --> 08:35.475
* There is a man *

08:35.475 --> 08:37.077
We published pieces

08:37.077 --> 08:39.446
promoting access
to contraception

08:39.446 --> 08:42.349
and safe and inexpensive
abortions for women.

08:42.349 --> 08:45.018
* Can his new wife *

08:45.018 --> 08:46.887
* Live out her life *

08:46.887 --> 08:48.288
Playboy has always had

08:48.288 --> 08:51.024
a strong editorial
point of view,

08:51.024 --> 08:52.826
and it's reflected
in everything we do.

08:52.826 --> 08:55.495
While the magazine
was a magazine

08:55.495 --> 08:57.397
of entertainment for men,

08:57.397 --> 08:59.632
the real intention
and message ran much deeper.

08:59.632 --> 09:01.634
* It's all right *

09:01.634 --> 09:03.736
* Say it's all right **

09:03.736 --> 09:07.941
**

09:09.409 --> 09:10.878
Fighting for change

09:10.878 --> 09:13.546
energized
the entire office,

09:13.546 --> 09:16.984
and soon, letters began
pouring in from readers,

09:16.984 --> 09:18.451
letting us know
that they also

09:18.451 --> 09:20.287
wanted to be part
of the debate.

09:20.287 --> 09:21.521
* Staring at
the boob tube *

09:21.521 --> 09:23.290
* Turning on
the big knob *

09:23.290 --> 09:25.292
* Trying to find
some life in the... *

09:25.292 --> 09:28.461
So I created The Playboy
Forum to open a dialogue.

09:28.461 --> 09:30.297
* Gonna deal
with Mary Jane *

09:30.297 --> 09:32.365
The forum became
an interchange of ideas

09:32.365 --> 09:34.501
between myself
and readers...

09:34.501 --> 09:36.169
* Obnoxious Joe
comes on the screen *

09:36.169 --> 09:39.072
...covering sex, marriage,

09:39.072 --> 09:42.375
religion,
police, economics...

09:42.375 --> 09:45.378
anything relevant
to social change.

09:45.378 --> 09:47.847
By having a conversation

09:47.847 --> 09:50.050
with millions
of men and women

09:50.050 --> 09:51.418
through The Playboy Forum,

09:51.418 --> 09:53.921
I think clearly
was a major contributor

09:53.921 --> 09:59.259
to people feeling comfortable
and not feeling so alone.

09:59.259 --> 10:00.693
Of course, a lot of people

10:00.693 --> 10:03.330
only wanted to talk
about Vietnam.

10:03.330 --> 10:05.032
**

10:05.032 --> 10:08.835
Many of our loyal readers
were now serving overseas,

10:08.835 --> 10:10.270
eager to voice
their opinions

10:10.270 --> 10:12.005
and share
their experiences

10:12.005 --> 10:13.673
from the front lines.

10:13.673 --> 10:15.842
**

10:15.842 --> 10:18.545
* Well it's evil, wicked *

10:18.545 --> 10:22.749
When Time magazine was still
promoting the war in Vietnam,

10:22.749 --> 10:27.087
The Playboy Forum gave
real soldiers a chance to say

10:27.087 --> 10:29.289
what their reality was
in Vietnam,

10:29.289 --> 10:32.725
and it was this place
to put actual testimony

10:32.725 --> 10:34.928
about what was going on.

10:37.264 --> 10:38.831
Abortion is still illegal.

10:38.831 --> 10:40.233
The Chicago Women's
Liberation Union

10:40.233 --> 10:42.002
are speaking out about it
and so should we.

10:42.002 --> 10:44.071
But then I took it
one step further,

10:44.071 --> 10:47.840
beyond the pages
of the magazine,

10:47.840 --> 10:50.843
and created
The Playboy Foundation...

10:50.843 --> 10:53.046
**

10:53.046 --> 10:56.316
...an organization dedicated
to fighting censorship

10:56.316 --> 10:59.386
and funding
civil rights groups.

11:01.321 --> 11:03.323
Hef had said that
The Playboy Foundation

11:03.323 --> 11:06.059
was intended to put his
money where his mouth was

11:06.059 --> 11:09.596
for issues that were not
just relevant to Playboy

11:09.596 --> 11:13.000
but were relevant to
a broader philosophy

11:13.000 --> 11:15.602
of what makes
for a just society.

11:15.602 --> 11:19.439
We donated hundreds
of thousands of dollars

11:19.439 --> 11:21.908
to the Kinsey Institute,

11:21.908 --> 11:25.645
an organization whose
research on sex and sexuality

11:25.645 --> 11:28.448
had inspired the founding
of the magazine.

11:28.448 --> 11:31.985
We involved ourselves in
landmark civil rights cases

11:31.985 --> 11:37.457
such as Roe v. Wade
and continued to support

11:37.457 --> 11:40.027
the African-American
struggle for freedom.

11:40.027 --> 11:43.096
**

11:46.099 --> 11:49.169
* When I left before *

11:49.169 --> 11:52.172
Across the country,
the civil rights movement

11:52.172 --> 11:56.743
was making
significant progress,

11:56.743 --> 12:00.780
and just a year earlier,
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

12:00.780 --> 12:05.818
was awarded the Nobel Peace
prize for his work.

12:05.818 --> 12:07.354
It was an incredible moment

12:07.354 --> 12:08.888
for the
civil rights movement,

12:08.888 --> 12:12.025
one we wanted to celebrate.

12:12.025 --> 12:14.861
So, in January of 1965,

12:14.861 --> 12:17.664
we published an interview
with Dr. King,

12:17.664 --> 12:20.233
the longest one
he ever granted.

12:20.233 --> 12:23.036
* But I keep coming back *

12:23.036 --> 12:24.971
When Playboy interviewed
Dr. King,

12:24.971 --> 12:26.239
it was a serious breakthrough

12:26.239 --> 12:28.775
because it was a chance
for another market.

12:28.775 --> 12:32.345
I mean, those days you
didn't have cable television.

12:32.345 --> 12:34.714
We didn't have much access.

12:34.714 --> 12:36.683
**

12:36.683 --> 12:40.320
MLK Jr.'s voice was
perfectly suited for Playboy.

12:40.320 --> 12:43.156
If you take a step back and
look at all the other pieces

12:43.156 --> 12:45.325
of what makes Playboy
Playboy,

12:45.325 --> 12:48.461
I can't think of another
magazine or media company

12:48.461 --> 12:51.598
where the conversation would
have been more appropriate.

12:51.598 --> 12:53.566
In his interview
with Playboy,

12:53.566 --> 12:56.336
King emphasized
how far we'd come,

12:56.336 --> 12:59.739
but he also explained
how far we had to go.

12:59.739 --> 13:01.441
**

13:01.441 --> 13:03.276
With a nonviolent movement,

13:03.276 --> 13:06.012
the end is to
convert the opponent

13:06.012 --> 13:07.914
and to bring about a society

13:07.914 --> 13:10.350
where all men will live
together as brothers

13:10.350 --> 13:12.519
and every man will
respect the dignity

13:12.519 --> 13:14.821
and worth
of human personality.

13:14.821 --> 13:16.889
**

13:16.889 --> 13:19.726
So, just months after being
featured in the magazine,

13:19.726 --> 13:25.365
King led a march
of 25,000 Americans,

13:25.365 --> 13:28.135
black and white,

13:28.135 --> 13:30.337
on a 54-mile journey

13:30.337 --> 13:32.872
from Selma, Alabama,

13:32.872 --> 13:34.507
to the state's capital,

13:34.507 --> 13:37.744
to show their support for
a new voting rights bill

13:37.744 --> 13:41.114
in the face
of ruthless opposition.

13:59.432 --> 14:00.700
After being attacked

14:00.700 --> 14:03.736
with nightsticks
and teargas,

14:03.736 --> 14:08.975
Dr. King and protesters
arrived in Montgomery.

14:08.975 --> 14:12.345
We are standing before
the forces of power

14:12.345 --> 14:14.013
in the State of Alabama,

14:14.013 --> 14:17.217
saying we ain't gonna
let nobody turn us around.

14:23.022 --> 14:28.661
What we saw in the news
shocked the entire nation.

14:28.661 --> 14:30.129
**

14:30.129 --> 14:33.400
There's no question that
the power of the media

14:33.400 --> 14:35.635
was a major force

14:35.635 --> 14:39.038
because it allowed
the civil rights protestors

14:39.038 --> 14:41.374
to get their message out

14:41.374 --> 14:43.910
by generating
images of oppression

14:43.910 --> 14:47.847
that were compelling
because they were so violent.

14:47.847 --> 14:49.382
**

14:49.382 --> 14:52.018
After considerable
public pressure,

14:52.018 --> 14:53.453
President Johnson passed

14:53.453 --> 14:57.490
the Voting Rights Act
of 1965, which outlawed

14:57.490 --> 15:00.727
discriminatory voting
practices based on race.

15:00.727 --> 15:02.429
**

15:02.429 --> 15:06.266
This bill will
strike down restrictions

15:06.266 --> 15:09.702
to voting in all elections.

15:14.507 --> 15:19.178
America was beginning
to see we needed change.

15:19.178 --> 15:23.650
**

15:29.055 --> 15:32.692
With progress being made
throughout the country,

15:32.692 --> 15:34.827
I wanted to break
the color barrier

15:34.827 --> 15:38.931
in all aspects
of our magazine.

15:38.931 --> 15:40.066
**

15:40.066 --> 15:41.100
Hi.

15:41.100 --> 15:42.335
Hi.

15:42.335 --> 15:44.070
If you could just
slip this on.

15:44.070 --> 15:48.975
* And when you come
to see me baby *

