15:54.947 --> 15:57.149
In March of 1965,

15:57.149 --> 15:58.718
we published
the first ever

15:58.718 --> 16:01.153
African-American
Playmate of the month,

16:01.153 --> 16:03.089
Jennifer Jackson.

16:03.089 --> 16:04.991
* I said baby *

16:04.991 --> 16:06.793
We found Jenny
working part-time

16:06.793 --> 16:08.895
in our Chicago
Playboy Club.

16:08.895 --> 16:11.964
She was a Bunny alongside
her twin sister, Jan,

16:11.964 --> 16:15.768
while studying at
a Chicago Teachers' College

16:15.768 --> 16:19.238
and doing some freelance
modeling on the side.

16:19.238 --> 16:21.808
**

16:21.808 --> 16:26.679
When Playboy published its
first African-American Playmate,

16:26.679 --> 16:30.049
it was a really
important comment

16:30.049 --> 16:32.619
on race relations
at the time.

16:32.619 --> 16:36.689
This was an important
acknowledgment of black women

16:36.689 --> 16:39.426
and their sexuality
and their beauty.

16:39.426 --> 16:40.693
* Sweet lovin' *

16:40.693 --> 16:42.595
* And that's all you need *

16:42.595 --> 16:44.731
* Oh yeah **

16:45.965 --> 16:47.834
**

16:47.834 --> 16:50.337
Reader responses
to Jennifer's centerfold

16:50.337 --> 16:52.772
were mostly positive,

16:52.772 --> 16:55.241
but we still got
some backlash,

16:55.241 --> 16:56.776
which convinced me

16:56.776 --> 16:59.879
there was still a lot
of work to be done.

16:59.879 --> 17:03.583
**

17:03.583 --> 17:04.884
I need it by 2 p.m.
Thank you.

17:04.884 --> 17:06.853
Uh, Spec.

17:06.853 --> 17:09.856
As Playboy became
more political,

17:09.856 --> 17:12.559
I continued
to personally oversee

17:12.559 --> 17:14.761
every page
of the magazine

17:14.761 --> 17:17.697
to make sure it was
as good as it could be.

17:17.697 --> 17:21.100
I am by nature
a perfectionist, anyway.

17:21.100 --> 17:24.471
I think the difference
between good and excellent

17:24.471 --> 17:27.273
is detail,
and I was consumed

17:27.273 --> 17:31.243
with every kind of detail
related to the company.

17:31.243 --> 17:34.481
**

17:38.785 --> 17:43.723
Soon, there didn't seem to
be enough hours in the day,

17:43.723 --> 17:50.262
so I relied on a little
orange pill, Dexedrine.

17:50.262 --> 17:52.665
**

17:52.665 --> 17:54.501
Dexedrine is an upper.

17:54.501 --> 17:56.002
It keeps you awake.

17:56.002 --> 17:59.606
It was originally
formulated as a drug

17:59.606 --> 18:01.073
to help you lose weight,

18:01.073 --> 18:06.312
but it has this other
quality that gives you pep

18:06.312 --> 18:07.814
and keeps you going.

18:07.814 --> 18:10.683
**

18:15.488 --> 18:19.291
* One, two, three, four... *

18:19.291 --> 18:22.662
**

18:22.662 --> 18:25.665
* Fortune has me
well in hand *

18:25.665 --> 18:27.767
I never tried hard drugs.

18:27.767 --> 18:31.070
I didn't believe in them.

18:31.070 --> 18:35.074
But Dexedrine
was completely legal

18:35.074 --> 18:39.479
and my doctor kept
prescribing it,

18:39.479 --> 18:42.615
so I told myself it
was a harmless little pill.

18:42.615 --> 18:45.585
* And brought you
to my bed *

18:45.585 --> 18:48.421
But pretty soon,
I couldn't live without it.

18:48.421 --> 18:50.457
* Everybody loves me baby *

18:50.457 --> 18:53.192
Page 37,
the robe is not...

18:53.192 --> 18:55.962
The colors here
are confusing.

18:55.962 --> 18:56.896
Page 29...

18:56.896 --> 18:57.964
Dexedrine helped Hefner

18:57.964 --> 19:00.700
write very long,
very dense memos

19:00.700 --> 19:02.969
and engage in
very long meetings.

19:02.969 --> 19:06.839
We used to go to meetings
at 4:00 in the afternoon.

19:06.839 --> 19:10.543
They would last until 6:00
the next morning.

19:10.543 --> 19:13.012
* To offend you *

19:13.012 --> 19:14.447
* Now *

19:14.447 --> 19:16.315
I would take them
as I needed them,

19:16.315 --> 19:20.720
but the work could often go
for 24 or 30 or more hours,

19:20.720 --> 19:22.555
so it was possible
in that timeframe

19:22.555 --> 19:25.592
to use 20, 25 pills.

19:25.592 --> 19:26.893
I don't think
I would have created

19:26.893 --> 19:29.762
the Playboy empire
without it.

19:29.762 --> 19:33.700
* Because everybody
loves me baby *

19:33.700 --> 19:36.202
He became very dependent
on Dexedrine.

19:36.202 --> 19:37.937
Scrap it.

19:37.937 --> 19:40.907
If he was taking the drug,

19:40.907 --> 19:44.110
that let him work for
two days or even more...

19:44.110 --> 19:46.378
* Everybody loves me baby *

19:46.378 --> 19:49.916
And then, he was so
exhausted that he'd crash.

19:49.916 --> 19:54.754
When he would awaken,
he would be a bit of a grouch.

19:54.754 --> 19:57.256
* What did I do
to offend you? *

19:57.256 --> 19:59.526
Yeah!

20:04.564 --> 20:05.732
Hef.

20:05.732 --> 20:06.866
I'll be done
with the new notes

20:06.866 --> 20:08.234
on the mansion piece
in ten minutes.

20:08.234 --> 20:10.102
Then I'm gonna go over
the Zwerin article.

20:10.102 --> 20:11.470
Tell everyone else to go over
what they're working on, too.

20:11.470 --> 20:12.539
I'm seeing
too many errors.

20:12.539 --> 20:13.740
I've already sent them home.

20:13.740 --> 20:16.075
What? You sent them home?

20:16.075 --> 20:17.644
They need to be
with their families.

20:17.644 --> 20:18.645
But they're working, Spec.

20:18.645 --> 20:19.846
It's after midnight.

20:19.846 --> 20:21.914
What, so people
can't work late now?

20:21.914 --> 20:23.049
Three nights in a row?
No, Hef, they can't.

20:23.049 --> 20:24.250
They can't keep
their eyes open.

20:24.250 --> 20:25.384
That's fine.

20:25.384 --> 20:26.385
Just means more work
for you and me.

20:26.385 --> 20:28.755
You cannot keep doing this.

20:28.755 --> 20:30.823
Oh, is it my fault
if the articles are shit?

20:30.823 --> 20:33.593
The articles are fine.
The problem is you.

20:33.593 --> 20:35.261
You've been up
for three days.

20:35.261 --> 20:37.329
You're a wreck.

20:37.329 --> 20:40.633
You are
killing yourself.

20:40.633 --> 20:41.634
I'm fine.

20:41.634 --> 20:43.035
You're not fine.

20:43.035 --> 20:44.637
If you want to leave,
then leave.

20:44.637 --> 20:46.706
Maybe I'm the only one
around here

20:46.706 --> 20:47.974
who still remembers
what it takes

20:47.974 --> 20:49.375
to put out a good magazine,

20:49.375 --> 20:51.778
but I am not going to
be lectured by you.

20:51.778 --> 20:53.212
Do you even hear yourself?

20:53.212 --> 20:55.514
Get out!

21:19.639 --> 21:21.407
When Hef became addicted,

21:21.407 --> 21:25.277
Hefner was accurately
described as self-centered,

21:25.277 --> 21:27.580
demanding, obsessive.

21:27.580 --> 21:30.683
Monstrous, even,
you could say.

21:30.683 --> 21:32.284
Really difficult
to deal with.

21:50.670 --> 21:55.174
My staff had reached
a breaking point,

21:55.174 --> 21:59.679
and it was clear that I
needed to make some changes.

22:10.690 --> 22:13.760
When I stopped
taking the Dexedrine,

22:13.760 --> 22:18.831
it took
the better part of a year

22:18.831 --> 22:22.669
for my own body to kick in
and give me back

22:22.669 --> 22:25.204
what I'd previously gotten
from the drug.

22:25.204 --> 22:29.108
If you start using an
artificial stimulus for it,

22:29.108 --> 22:31.944
then the body starts
depending on that,

22:31.944 --> 22:35.547
and it needs more of it,
and, you know,

22:35.547 --> 22:37.884
they do all those jokes
about get high on life,

22:37.884 --> 22:39.618
but it's true.

22:39.618 --> 22:43.389
**

22:43.389 --> 22:45.491
While I was
regaining my health,

22:45.491 --> 22:47.760
Playboy was getting
bigger every month

22:47.760 --> 22:49.528
and the effects
of our hard work

22:49.528 --> 22:53.465
could be seen in every
aspect of the company.

22:53.465 --> 22:55.501
* Oh my love *

22:55.501 --> 22:58.671
We had 15 clubs operating
within the United States,

22:58.671 --> 23:02.809
including locations
in Los Angeles and Miami,

23:02.809 --> 23:05.477
and international locations

23:05.477 --> 23:08.948
in Montreal,
Manila, and Jamaica.

23:08.948 --> 23:11.417
Originally, when we
started off the first one

23:11.417 --> 23:12.952
in Chicago back in '59,

23:12.952 --> 23:15.021
we had no notion
it would be so successful.

23:15.021 --> 23:18.024
* So many times *

23:18.024 --> 23:20.492
* You're gonna be lonely *

23:20.492 --> 23:23.595
* So many times
you're gonna be blue *

23:23.595 --> 23:27.333
By the end of the 1960s,
the magazine was selling

23:27.333 --> 23:30.402
an average of 5.5 million
issues per month

23:30.402 --> 23:32.404
and Playboy's profits
had climbed

23:32.404 --> 23:34.306
to $80 million a year.

23:34.306 --> 23:35.775
**

23:35.775 --> 23:39.645
I decided the time had come
to make a big statement

23:39.645 --> 23:43.682
and establish ourselves
as an American institution.

23:43.682 --> 23:45.885
**

23:51.623 --> 23:54.994
So I purchased the
37-floor Palmolive Building

23:54.994 --> 23:59.098
on Michigan Ave.
for $2.7 million

23:59.098 --> 24:03.002
and put our name across it
in nine-foot letters.

24:03.002 --> 24:04.570
* She asked me maybe *

24:04.570 --> 24:06.638
* If I could
share her sorrow *

24:06.638 --> 24:07.940
Not only was it

24:07.940 --> 24:11.077
one of Chicago's
most iconic buildings,

24:11.077 --> 24:13.312
but as a kid,
I'd looked out my window

24:13.312 --> 24:17.716
and seen the spotlight
on top light up the city.

24:17.716 --> 24:19.986
When Hefner puts Playboy

24:19.986 --> 24:22.789
in big, bright shining letters

24:22.789 --> 24:25.024
on the Palmolive Building
in Chicago,

24:25.024 --> 24:29.128
the Playboy brand becomes
part of the skyline.

24:29.128 --> 24:31.397
The argument is over, right?

24:31.397 --> 24:33.332
The empire is now here,

24:33.332 --> 24:35.935
and there's really nothing
you can do about it.

24:35.935 --> 24:37.136
* The promised land *

24:37.136 --> 24:38.771
* Hang on 'til then *

24:38.771 --> 24:41.173
* As best as you can *

24:43.075 --> 24:44.743
Stand on this one, the mark
here that we've placed.

24:44.743 --> 24:48.347
Yeah, that's the one.
Perfect.

24:48.347 --> 24:49.348
Holding the pipe?

24:49.348 --> 24:51.217
Yes.

24:51.217 --> 24:56.856
As for me, after years of
fighting to prove ourselves,

24:56.856 --> 24:58.457
I ended up on the cover

24:58.457 --> 25:04.430
of one of the most
respected publications,

25:04.430 --> 25:06.698
Time magazine.

25:06.698 --> 25:08.167
To make it onto the cover

25:08.167 --> 25:11.904
of Time magazine
in '67 was huge.

25:11.904 --> 25:14.240
This is the recognition
of the establishment

25:14.240 --> 25:17.076
that you are a player,
right?

25:17.076 --> 25:18.177
Presidents are on the cover,

25:18.177 --> 25:20.079
dictators are on the cover,
right?

25:20.079 --> 25:23.549
That's who makes the cover
of Time magazine.

25:25.017 --> 25:27.153
He had arrived.

25:29.655 --> 25:32.859
Being on the cover of Time
validated everything

25:32.859 --> 25:36.562
I'd been doing
for the last 15 years.

25:42.101 --> 25:44.203
Here we have panels
along this wall,

25:44.203 --> 25:45.771
similar to what we use
in the clubs.

25:45.771 --> 25:47.506
It should look nice.
This is the bar.

25:47.506 --> 25:49.408
Made it L-shaped
so we can have people

25:49.408 --> 25:52.011
along both sides
and not miss anything.

25:52.011 --> 25:53.345
Glasses here.

25:53.345 --> 25:56.682
Uh, Bobbie,
we're in a meeting.

25:56.682 --> 25:58.150
Police have issued
an all-points bulletin

25:58.150 --> 25:59.818
for a well-dressed
young white man

25:59.818 --> 26:01.387
seen running
from the scene.

26:01.387 --> 26:03.890
Dr. King was standing
on the balcony

26:03.890 --> 26:05.892
of his second-floor
hotel room tonight

26:05.892 --> 26:08.194
when, according
to a companion,

26:08.194 --> 26:10.662
a shot was fired
from across the street.

26:10.662 --> 26:12.064
In the friend's words,

26:12.064 --> 26:14.100
the bullet exploded
in his face.

26:14.100 --> 26:19.005
April 4th, 1968, was a day
I will never forget.

26:19.005 --> 26:21.040
...in the civil rights
movement

26:21.040 --> 26:22.841
were on the scene
almost immediately.

26:22.841 --> 26:26.145
They rushed the 39-year-old
Negro leader to a hospital,

26:26.145 --> 26:28.981
where he died of
a bullet wound in the neck.

26:28.981 --> 26:31.250
**

26:31.250 --> 26:33.953
The death of
Martin Luther King,

26:33.953 --> 26:39.725
that just seemed
to stop time.

26:39.725 --> 26:42.929
It was horrible,
it was unimaginable,

26:42.929 --> 26:45.064
but you didn't need
to imagine it.

26:45.064 --> 26:47.499
And people
were really saying,

26:47.499 --> 26:53.172
"What kind of world are we in?
What kind of people are we?

26:53.172 --> 26:55.574
Who's gonna
stop this sort of thing?"

26:55.574 --> 26:57.176
**

26:57.176 --> 26:59.711
As riots broke out
across the country,

26:59.711 --> 27:04.183
leaders tried desperately
to calm the nation.

27:04.183 --> 27:06.618
What we need
in the United States

27:06.618 --> 27:08.320
is not division.

27:08.320 --> 27:09.821
What we need
in the United States

27:09.821 --> 27:11.857
is not hatred.

27:11.857 --> 27:15.327
And no speech did more to
bring the country together

27:15.327 --> 27:16.996
than Robert F. Kennedy's...

27:16.996 --> 27:19.365
...but is love and wisdom

27:19.365 --> 27:21.867
and compassion
toward one another.

27:21.867 --> 27:24.536
...who'd experienced his
own brother's assassination

27:24.536 --> 27:26.605
just under
five years earlier.

27:26.605 --> 27:30.142
...within our country,
whether they be white

27:30.142 --> 27:31.978
or whether they be black.

27:40.652 --> 27:43.522
**

28:09.648 --> 28:11.450
Martin Luther King Jr.

28:11.450 --> 28:15.221
was laid to rest
in Atlanta, Georgia.

28:16.822 --> 28:21.560
Over 100,000 people attended
the funeral procession.

28:23.962 --> 28:27.433
The big piece which I think
resonated with my dad

28:27.433 --> 28:31.037
was that Dr. King
had died for something

28:31.037 --> 28:34.873
that was a lot more
than just him,

28:34.873 --> 28:39.411
that he'd given his life
for change...

28:39.411 --> 28:42.114
**

28:42.114 --> 28:46.685
...and that change was the
challenge of finding a way

28:46.685 --> 28:47.853
to live in a world

28:47.853 --> 28:51.890
where people could make
their own choices freely.

28:51.890 --> 28:55.361
**

28:59.665 --> 29:01.400
I knew what a blow

29:01.400 --> 29:04.103
his death was for
the civil rights movement

29:04.103 --> 29:06.372
and the country as a whole,

29:06.372 --> 29:07.706
and I wanted to figure out

29:07.706 --> 29:09.275
the best way
to honor his memory.

29:09.275 --> 29:12.411
"A promised land
of true equality."

29:12.411 --> 29:13.812
Weeks before
his assassination,

29:13.812 --> 29:17.216
Playboy received
an essay from Dr. King

29:17.216 --> 29:20.252
called A Testament of Hope,

29:20.252 --> 29:22.821
a work that would
tragically become

29:22.821 --> 29:25.491
his final written words.

29:25.491 --> 29:27.259
"In his final
published statement,

29:27.259 --> 29:28.994
"the civil rights leader
points the way out

29:28.994 --> 29:30.496
"of America's racial turmoil

29:30.496 --> 29:32.931
into the promised land
of equality."

29:32.931 --> 29:36.034
That's better,
but add "fallen"

29:36.034 --> 29:37.203
before "civil rights leader"

29:37.203 --> 29:39.938
and add "true"
before equality.

29:39.938 --> 29:42.608
We knew that publishing
his passionate words

29:42.608 --> 29:46.545
was the best way
we could honor his legacy.

29:46.545 --> 29:52.118
But soon, another tragedy
rocked the nation.

29:57.289 --> 29:58.990
If there's a doctor
in the house,

29:58.990 --> 30:00.226
I want to see him
right here.

30:00.226 --> 30:02.261
Everybody else,
please stay back.

30:05.297 --> 30:07.833
Oh, no!

30:11.603 --> 30:15.474
Before we could adjust
in any measure

30:15.474 --> 30:19.445
to Dr. King's assassination,
April 4th, 1968,

30:19.445 --> 30:23.382
Robert Kennedy killed
June the 5th in Los Angeles.

30:23.382 --> 30:27.253
It just left us
pained and hurt,

30:27.253 --> 30:30.522
as if all hope
had been lost.

30:30.522 --> 30:33.091
We were numb.

30:33.091 --> 30:37.563
**

30:37.563 --> 30:42.033
Soon, that grief
turned to anger.

30:42.033 --> 30:46.672
* In the early dawn
the Bishop's men *

30:46.672 --> 30:49.107
* Shivered in the damp *

30:49.107 --> 30:52.411
* Who prayed that
wives and families *

30:52.411 --> 30:56.982
* Might see them
once again *

30:56.982 --> 30:59.851
**

31:02.654 --> 31:04.390
In the summer of '68,

31:04.390 --> 31:07.559
the fear and anxiety
of the long hot summer,

31:07.559 --> 31:12.198
you had all of the issues
and all of the anger

31:12.198 --> 31:15.133
that had been building up.

31:15.133 --> 31:17.703
It turns
into absolute mayhem.

31:17.703 --> 31:20.372
* The ground mist hid
the patrol's approach *

31:20.372 --> 31:22.674
* As they drew
close enough to show *

31:22.674 --> 31:25.977
It was a time of revolution
and some of it was violent.

31:25.977 --> 31:28.947
It was a time of questioning
old mores and values.

31:28.947 --> 31:30.916
* Of pure white sand *

31:30.916 --> 31:34.119
It was questioning a lot
of the fundamental views

31:34.119 --> 31:36.322
that people saw were hurtful.

31:36.322 --> 31:39.258
* At evensong
both camps reviewed *

31:39.258 --> 31:41.593
* Their sad depleted ranks *

31:41.593 --> 31:45.964
To make matters worse,
by the summer of 1968,

31:45.964 --> 31:48.900
the Vietnam War was
spiraling out of control.

31:48.900 --> 31:53.205
* Gave God their
grateful thanks *

31:53.205 --> 31:57.443
**

31:57.443 --> 32:01.647
Even while the search
for peace was going on,

32:01.647 --> 32:04.550
North Vietnam
rushed their preparations

32:04.550 --> 32:08.787
for a savage assault
on the people,

32:08.787 --> 32:10.021
the government,

32:10.021 --> 32:13.124
and the allies
of South Vietnam.

32:13.124 --> 32:15.594
The North Vietnamese
launched

32:15.594 --> 32:17.429
their most
brutal campaign yet

32:17.429 --> 32:19.231
against American troops,

32:19.231 --> 32:21.767
a series of
surprise bomb attacks

32:21.767 --> 32:25.937
that would come to be known
as the Tet Offensive.

32:27.739 --> 32:29.808
The Viet Cong
simultaneously attacked

32:29.808 --> 32:33.312
just about every major city
and town in South Vietnam,

32:33.312 --> 32:34.746
and it was a new war.

32:34.746 --> 32:37.783
After over a decade of war,

32:37.783 --> 32:41.453
nearly 20,000 American
soldiers had been killed

32:41.453 --> 32:44.956
and it seemed there
was no end in sight.

32:44.956 --> 32:48.494
**

32:48.494 --> 32:50.195
Just hoping to stay alive
from day to day.

32:50.195 --> 32:52.197
Everybody just wants to go
back home and go to school.

32:52.197 --> 32:53.465
That's about it.

32:53.465 --> 32:54.900
Have you lost any friends?

32:54.900 --> 32:57.503
Quite a few.
We lost one the other day.

32:57.503 --> 32:59.905
This whole thing stinks,
really.

33:02.240 --> 33:07.279
**

33:11.350 --> 33:14.286
But as strongly as
Playboy opposed the war

33:14.286 --> 33:17.022
in the pages
of the magazine,

33:17.022 --> 33:21.727
we knew many of our readers
were stationed overseas,

33:21.727 --> 33:24.463
and we wanted to do
what we could to help.

33:24.463 --> 33:27.766
* One, two, three, four
sha la la la la la *

33:27.766 --> 33:29.835
We teamed up with the USO,

33:29.835 --> 33:34.205
sending our 1965 Playmate
of the Year, Jo Collins,

33:34.205 --> 33:36.174
to visit the soldiers.

33:36.174 --> 33:38.577
Miss Jo Collins,
ladies and gentlemen.

33:40.379 --> 33:44.850
So, Lieutenant Jack Price
of the 173rd Airborne Brigade

33:44.850 --> 33:46.785
in Vietnam sent a letter
to Hugh Hefner,

33:46.785 --> 33:48.387
saying that
him and his company

33:48.387 --> 33:51.923
wanted to chip in $150 to
have the Playmate of the Year

33:51.923 --> 33:53.825
deliver a lifetime
subscription,

33:53.825 --> 33:56.828
so we flew over to Saigon
and delivered it.

33:56.828 --> 33:58.797
Isn't that a sweet story?

34:00.265 --> 34:02.601
* Two, three, four *

34:02.601 --> 34:05.036
* Sha la la la la la
live for today *

34:05.036 --> 34:08.106
It was a uniquely Playboy
way to build morale,

34:08.106 --> 34:10.342
and while it wasn't
going to bring them home,

34:10.342 --> 34:12.878
I hoped it could at least
brighten the mood

34:12.878 --> 34:15.647
of the men fighting for our
country, even momentarily.

34:15.647 --> 34:17.549
* Sha la la la la la
live for today *

34:17.549 --> 34:19.785
* Live for today *

34:22.588 --> 34:24.890
Also, we thought
it would be fun

34:24.890 --> 34:28.126
to have two floors and see
how that opens up the space.

34:28.126 --> 34:31.763
1968 had been
a year of chaos.

34:31.763 --> 34:34.833
It was clear that Americans
had grown disheartened

34:34.833 --> 34:38.404
by what they were
seeing on TV,

34:38.404 --> 34:40.205
so I came up with an idea

